<p>Strictly speaking, it doesnâ€™t necessarily do anything.</p>

<p>If a Makefile has a target named check, then make check will â€œbuildâ€ that target. Itâ€™s typically a phony target, meaning that it is a make-scripted command rather than a file named â€œcheckâ€ that gets created.</p>

<p>The gnu project advises that all gnu software should include a make check target that runs post-build tests in the build directory, so make check can be used frequently on packages distributed from the FSF. Other projects will sometimes follow this convention as well.
